        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will concentrate on the continuum emission in this program, and thus the correlator setting with the widest bandwidth is selected. The frequency settings is optimize for the continuum emission, covering the best frequency ranges in atmospheric transmission.  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To understand the origin of the lopsided disk, the measurement of its radial width at resolution better than the pressure scale heght is essential. The pressure scale height is estimated to be 17 AU (at r=160AU), corresponding to 0.12" (at r=1.1") at the distance to HD 142527. Furthermore, if the lopsided structure is created by a protoplanet, its circumplanetary disk whose radius is smaller than the Hill radius will be detected. The Hill radius for a protoplanet with 1-Jupiter mass is caliculated to be 8 AU, or 0.06" at r=160AU. To resolve any kind of features with such a size scale, the beam size of 0.04" is selected for Band 7. 
For the largest angular scale, 0.4" on the other hand, is estimated from the upper limit to the Gaussian's width of the model disk that accounts for the radial profile of dust continuum taken in cycle 0. This is just slightly smaller than the maximum recoverable sizescale, and it is therefore marginal to fully recover the continuum flux only with the Cycle 3 data. We can, however, add the visibility data at the same frequency taken in Cycle 0 to recover any missing flux if needed. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our science goal is to image the dust continuum emission from the disk around HD 142527
at high angular resolution. Cycle 0 observations in Band 7 revealed the lopsided structure of the disk in dust continuum emission. A radial profile in each PA can be well described by a Gaussian function. The maximum and minimum peaks among these Gaussians are 217 mJy/beam and 7 mJy/beam, respectively, at 336 GHz with a 0.4" beam. The brightest feature will be a great help in successful self-calibration in these long-baseline observations. 
The target sensitivity is determined so that the expected brightness at the lowest peak of the radial profile (in PA=220), which is calculated under the assumption that flux density is proportional to (frequency)^3, will be detected at 4\sigma-level. The resultant target at 0.04" resolution is 18 uJy/beam. This sensitivity will cover most regions of the disk, allowing us to discuss the disk structure and opacity index (\beta) even in lower brightness regions where the emission becomes optically thin.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
