    <prp:abstract>We propose high-resolution observations of dust continuum emission from the disk around HD 142527 in (i) 0.04'' resolution at 342 GHz and (ii) 0.1'' resolution at 145 GHz. Cycle 0 observations reveal lopsided structure in dust continuum with a very bright peak, making this object an ideal target for long-baseline observations. Model fitting to the observed radial profile of the continuum emission in each PA shows that the contrast of dust surface density is ~ 70, and the profile can be reproduced by surface density distribution in Gaussian form. However, the derived radial width is ~ 50 AU, just comparable to the beam size in Cycle 0 and should be regarded as the upper limit. A measurement of the radial width with accuracy better than the pressure scale height (&lt; 17 AU) is essential for understanding the origin and nature of the lopsided structure. The other clue for understanding the disk nature is spatial variation of dust size distribution. To address this issue, we will map the distribution of opacity index \beta based on the dual-frequency imaging. Its azimuthal structure is especially important, because it will give us \beta-variation as a function of (surface) density. </prp:abstract>
